        "created_at": "2025-07-07T04:47:50.577Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I came across Daniel Bernsteinâ€™s Crypto blog, which discusses how NIST promoted ML-KEM as the top choice. Apparently, NIST used flawed math to create fake arguments for it. Since Signal uses ML-KEM, this is concerning.</p>\n<p>Here the link to Bernsteinâ€™s blog: <a href=\"https://blog.cr.yp.to/20231003-countcorrectly.html\" class=\"inline-onebox\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">cr.yp.to: 2023.10.03: The inability to count correctly</a></p>\n<p>As I understand it, Bernstein does not claim that ML-KEM has been fully broken, but rather highlights how the 512-bit variant was chosen to fulfill the requirements and keep the 768-bit and 1024-bit variants in the NIST competition.</p>\n<p>What are your thoughts on this? Does Signal plan to transition to alternative KEMs in the future? Why did Signal choose ML-KEM over other options, such as Classic McEliece? Is it simply because ML-KEM is currently the only standardized option?</p>\n<p>I looked up the libsignal code, and it appears that Signal uses ML-KEM-768 and ML-KEM-1024. Does anyone know which one is used when? From my understanding, many potential security issues could be avoided by using a larger key size. So, why not use ML-KEM-1024 by default?</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 3,
        "updated_at": "2025-07-07T04:47:50.577Z",
